{
  "style": "IEEE",
  "texts": [
    "• Geographic concentration: AI data centers tend to cluster in regions with low electricity prices, ample land and water resources, and favorable policy environments.",
    "In the U.S., for example, fifteen states (most notably Virginia, Texas, and California) accounted for about 80% of total data center demand in 2023 [14].",
    "Such concentration effect further intensifies local grid stress, and many regional grids cannot accommodate large-scale integration of data centers without substantial infrastructure upgrades [22].",
    "As such, the rapid expansion of AI data centers poses unprecedented challenges to modern power systems.",
    "To sustain the fast pace of AI innovation and the continued growth of AI infrastructure, it is essential to establish a deep understanding of AI data center loads and their interactions with the grid, and to develop effective solution strategies that ensure reliable and sustainable power system operation.A growing number of recent articles and reports [7], [8], [14], [23]- [25] have drawn considerable attention to the surging electricity demand of AI data centers and their implications for the power sector."
  ],
